		<description><![CDATA[Knowing the Trinity in unity is the fruit and end (fructus et finis) of our entire life. —Thomas Aquinas, Scriptum super libros Sententiarum, lib. I, dist. 2, expositio textus; trans. John Boyle, p. 34. (Cognitio enim Trinitatis in unitate est fructus et finis totius vitae nostrae.)]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote><p><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/ThomasAquinas.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-866" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/ThomasAquinas-220x300.jpg" alt="Thomas Aquinas as depicted in Valle Romita Polyptych by Gentile da Fabriano" width="220" height="300" /></a>Knowing the Trinity in unity is the fruit and end (<em>fructus et finis</em>) of our entire life.</p></blockquote>
<p><span style="font-size: .8em;">—Thomas Aquinas, <em>Scriptum super libros Sententiarum</em>, lib. I, dist. 2, expositio textus; trans. <a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=BwLDngEACAAJ">John Boyle</a>, p. 34. (<em>Cognitio enim Trinitatis in unitate est fructus et finis totius vitae nostrae</em>.)</span></p>
